Q1 You have a low-priv domain user. You enumerate and find a user with an SPN set.

    What attack do you perform? Kerberoasting
    What’s the dependency for success? Weak/crackable password
    What’s your next step after getting the result? Cracking offline -> reuse creds -> enumerate with new privs


Q2 You compromise a machine and have local admin, but no domain creds yet.

    What are your top 3 immediate actions? dump creds from memory (mimikatz or beacon> logonpasswords), check for active sessions, dump lsass, check files for creds, check sctasks/services
    NOTE: local admin = credential access opportunity, not instant win


Q3 You dump creds and find: a domain user with no obvious privileges, but they are part of a group that has GenericWrite over another user

    What does that allow you to do? take over the user account, change password, add an SPN and kerberoast them, add to group, modify attributes


Q4 You find unconstrained delegation on a server.

    What’s the abuse path? can be used to extract TGTs as the server caches TGTs of users who authenticate
    What do you need to wait for or trigger? high-value user (like DA) to authenticate, we can use rubeus to monitor and coerce authentication


Q5 You have a user account with SeImpersonatePrivilege on a machine.

    What attack do you use? Use potato-family exploit
    What’s the typical end result? SYSTEM, which gives us cred dumping power to get DA

Q6 You run BloodHound and see: User → WriteDACL → Group → Domain Admins
    What’s your move? we control the ACL of the group, so we can grant ourselves full control / generic all over the group then add ourselves

NOTE:
    Whenever you land on a host:
        Am I local admin?
